06336nam a22009735i 9783110688047DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106880477 a10.1515/97831106880472doi  a(DE-B1597)541496  a(OCoLC)1163878418  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aWord, Phrase, and Sentence in Relation :bAncient Grammars and Contexts /ced. by Paola Cotticelli-Kurras. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XI, 217 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v9900tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tList of tables -- tClause relations in Ancient Greek Grammatical tradition? -- tLinguistic thought in Rome before Varro -- tῬῆμα and Λόγος in Aristotle: what can (or cannot) they mean? -- tἐμπειρία, τέχνη, and beyond. Recent controversies on the ‘analogy vs. anomaly quarrel’ in historical and theoretical context -- tOn the metalinguistic passage from διάβασις and μετάβασις by Apollonius Dyscolus to transitio by Priscian -- t‘Quis vel qui’. A controversial classification in Latin grammatical sources -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex Rerum et Nominum -- tIndex Auctorum Antiquorum et Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributions contained in this volume offer a multidisciplinary approach into the history of the parts of speech and their role in building phrases and sentences. They fulfill a current interest for syntactic problems for combining recent linguistic theories with the long tradition of the Classical studies. The studies cover a chronological range reaching from Aristotle to Priscian and deal with concepts like ῥῆμα and λóγος, or the two Aristotelian expressions λέξις εἰρομένη and λέξις κατεστραμμένη as well as διάβασις and μετάβασις in Apollonius Dyscolos and the corresponding Latin term transitio and finally the Latin pronouns qui or quis. Through the metalinguistic approach the authors tackle syntactic structures like dependency or government, syntactic features or properties such as transitivity or subject and predicate or the development of the syntactic role of pronouns in introducing relative sentences. Furthermore, in providing testimonies of the historical existence of the controversy anomaly-analogy, the history of this quarrel is drawn from the Alexandrinian tradition to the Latin one with emphasis on the studium grammaticae as a development of an independent field of study.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aGreek languagexSyntaxvCongresses. 0aLatin languagexSyntaxvCongresses. 4aAntike. 4aGrammatikographie. 4aSprachwissenschaft. 4aSyntax.  aAncient grammaticography.  arelative pronouns.  asyntax.1 aCotticelli-Kurras, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotticelli-Kurras, Paola, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuso, Antonella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraffi, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthaios, Stephanos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeneghel, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerlin Defanti, Stella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOniga, Renato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyt